  "complaint": {
    "factual_background": "MyLife.com, Inc. and its CEO Jeffrey Tinsley sold consumer background reports by displaying deceptive 'teaser' search results that falsely implied searched-for individuals had criminal, arrest, or sex offender records—even when none existed—in order to induce consumers to purchase subscriptions. The company enrolled subscribers in automatically renewing subscriptions without clearly disclosing material terms, charged lump-sum multi-month fees without clear notice, and made cancellation extremely difficult by requiring phone calls to uncooperative or unavailable customer service agents. MyLife also conducted deceptive outbound telemarketing that misrepresented subscription benefits and cancellation/refund policies. Additionally, MyLife functioned as a consumer reporting agency under the FCRA but failed to maintain required procedures for verifying subscriber purposes, assuring report accuracy, or providing required User Notices.",
    "representations_made": [
      {
        "description": "Represented that searched-for individuals had criminal or sexual offender record histories that users could view after purchasing a MyLife subscription, even when such records did not exist",
        "quoted_text": "40. Defendants represent to MyLife.com users that searched-for individuals had criminal or sexual offender records histories that users could view after paying money to MyLife.",
        "verified": true,
        "confidence": 1,
        "source_paragraph": 40,
        "quote_start_line": 373,
        "quote_end_line": 375
      },
      {
        "description": "Displayed 'Court, Arrest, or Criminal Records' and 'Sex Offender Status' sections with prominent 'View' buttons and 'may have' language, leading users to conclude the searched-for individual in fact has such records",
        "quoted_text": "28. The prominent “View" buttons for "Court, Arrest or Criminal Records" and "Sex Offender Records," together with statements that the search subject "may have" such records, lead reasonable users to conclude that the searched-for individual in fact has arrest, criminal, or sex offender records, even if they do not.”,
        "verified": true,
        "confidence": 1,
        "source_paragraph": 28,
        "quote_start_line": 282,
        "quote_end_line": 285
      },
      {
        "description": "Represented that the Reputation Score was 'based on public information, gathered from government, social, and other sources, plus personal reviews written by others,' and that '[r]eputation is more important than credit'",
        "quoted_text": "someone else, or arrived at MyLife.com via a search engine, the website displayed a “teaser" background report ("Teaser Background Report"). The Teaser Background Report featured a "Reputation Score," which Defendants represented was "based on public information, gathered from government, social, and other sources, plus personal reviews written by others." Advertisements for MyLife’s Reputation Score claim that "[r]eputation is more important than credit."”,
        "verified": true,
        "confidence": 1,
        "source_paragraph": 26,
        "quote_start_line": 268,
        "quote_end_line": 273
      },
      {
        "description": "Failed to clearly and conspicuously disclose all material terms of subscriptions before obtaining billing information, including that multi-month subscriptions would be charged as a lump sum rather than monthly installments",
        "quoted_text": "32. The subscription pricing plans displayed to prospective subscribers do not clearly or conspicuously disclose all material terms of the transaction before obtaining the subscriber’s billing information. For example, for a subscriber buying a 12-month subscription for $6.95/month, it was unclear whether, on completing their purchase, the subscriber would be charged the monthly rate of $6.95/month or, as was the case, $83.40—the total lump sum amount for all 12 months.",
        "verified": true,
        "confidence": 1,
        "source_paragraph": 32,
        "quote_start_line": 305,
        "quote_end_line": 310
      },
      {
        "description": "Failed to clearly disclose that subscriptions automatically renewed and that cancellation required calling a customer service line before the subscription period ended",
        "quoted_text": "33. Defendants also fail to make clear to prospective subscribers that everyone who bought a MyLife.com subscription is enrolled in an automatically renewing subscription, although subscribers in California, Oregon, Washington, and Connecticut were given the option to refuse automatic renewal. An automatically renewing subscription is a negative option feature, meaning that when a subscriber’s subscription period was set to end, Defendants automatically charged them for a renewal subscription unless the subscriber affirmatively acted to cancel his or her subscription.",
        "verified": true,
        "confidence": 1,
        "source_paragraph": 33,
        "quote_start_line": 311,
        "quote_end_line": 318
      },
      {
        "description": "Made misleading and deceptive statements during telemarketing calls about subscription benefits, cancellation policies, and refund policies",
        "quoted_text": "30. MyLife also conducted outbound telemarketing campaigns to prospective customers. On these outbound calls, MyLife made materially misleading and deceptive statements and omissions, including about the benefits of a subscription and about MyLife’s cancellation and refund policies and practices.",
        "verified": true,
        "confidence": 1,
        "source_paragraph": 30,
        "quote_start_line": 295,
        "quote_end_line": 298
      },
      {
        "description": "Customer service agents made false statements about the ease of cancellation, the existence of automatic renewal, and the availability of refunds when subscribers called to cancel",
        "quoted_text": "36. If callers did reach customer-service agents in seeking to cancel their MyLife subscriptions or to obtain refunds, those MyLife agents made misleading and deceptive statements and omissions to the callers, including false statements about the ease with which subscribers could cancel their subscriptions, the existence of an automatic-renewal feature, and the availability of refunds. During calls with MyLife customer-service agents, subscribers who tried to cancel their premium subscriptions have faced intense pressure to renew their subscriptions or were simply not permitted to cancel their subscriptions or to obtain refunds.",
        "verified": true,
        "confidence": 1,
        "source_paragraph": 36,
        "quote_start_line": 336,
        "quote_end_line": 343
      },
      {
        "description": "Promoted MyLife background reports for use in employment, tenant screening, loans, and housing—purposes covered by the FCRA—without maintaining required FCRA procedures",
        "quoted_text": "25. Since at least 2015, in their marketing and advertising, Defendants have promoted the use of MyLife background reports in establishing an individual’s eligibility for employment, loans, and housing, displaying testimonials in which customers praised MyLife’s background reports as helpful for such purposes.",
        "verified": true,
        "confidence": 1,
        "source_paragraph": 25,
        "quote_start_line": 263,
        "quote_end_line": 266
      }
    ],
    "counts": [
      {
        "count_number": 1,
        "title": "Deceptive Misrepresentation of Criminal/Sex Offender Records (FTC Act Section 5(a))",
        "representation": "Defendants represented to MyLife.com users that searched-for individuals had criminal or sexual offender record histories that users could view after paying money to MyLife.",
        "fact": "In many instances, the searched-for individuals do not have criminal or sexual offender records, or they have only minor traffic citations.",
        "conclusion": "Defendants' representations to the contrary are false or misleading and constitute deceptive acts or practices in violation of Section 5 of the FTC Act, 15 U.S.C. § 45(a)."
      },
      {
        "count_number": 2,
        "title": "Telemarketing Sales Rule Violations",
        "representation": "In the sale of subscriptions via telemarketing, Defendants failed to disclose truthfully and in a clear and conspicuous manner all material terms of their refund or cancellation policies, and misrepresented the benefits of a MyLife subscription, their refund and cancellation policies, and the negative-option features of the subscription.",
        "fact": "Defendants have a policy of not making refunds and of discouraging cancellations, and the negative-option auto-renewal feature was not clearly disclosed.",
        "conclusion": "Defendants' acts or practices violate the TSR, 16 C.F.R. § 310.3(a)(1)-(2), and are therefore violations of a rule promulgated under Section 18 of the FTC Act. Defendants' violations are willful and knowing."
      },
      {
        "count_number": 3,
        "title": "Restore Online Shoppers' Confidence Act (ROSCA) Violations",
        "representation": "Defendants sold MyLife.com subscriptions through a negative-option feature without clearly and conspicuously disclosing before obtaining billing information that: the total cost would be due immediately as a lump sum; subscriptions auto-renewed unless affirmatively cancelled; cancellation required a phone call before subscription end; and customer service agents would prevent or discourage cancellation.",
        "fact": "Defendants failed to clearly disclose material transaction terms and failed to provide a simple mechanism for subscribers to stop recurring charges.",
        "conclusion": "Defendants' acts or practices violate Section 4 of ROSCA, 15 U.S.C. § 8403, and are therefore a violation of a rule promulgated under Section 18 of the FTC Act. Defendants' violations are willful and knowing."
      },
      {
        "count_number": 4,
        "title": "FCRA Violation — Furnishing Consumer Reports Without Permissible Purpose",
        "representation": "Defendants, as a consumer reporting agency, furnished consumer reports (Background Reports) to MyLife subscribers without having reason to believe those subscribers had permissible purposes under FCRA Section 604.",
        "fact": "Defendants regularly provided consumer reports without knowing subscribers' purposes and without employing any procedures for requesting or identifying each subscriber's purpose.",
        "conclusion": "Pursuant to Section 621(a)(1) of the FCRA, 15 U.S.C. § 1681s(a)(1), these acts and practices constitute unfair or deceptive acts or practices in violation of Section 5(a) of the FTC Act. Defendants' violations are willful and knowing."
      },
      {
        "count_number": 5,
        "title": "FCRA Violation — Failure to Maintain Reasonable Procedures and Provide User Notices",
        "representation": "Defendants failed to maintain reasonable procedures required by FCRA Sections 607(a) and 607(b) and failed to provide required User Notices under FCRA Section 607(d).",
        "fact": "Defendants did not require subscribers to identify themselves or certify their purpose; did not verify subscriber identity or use certification; did not limit furnishing of reports to permissible purposes; did not assure maximum possible accuracy of report information; and did not provide User Notices to recipients of Background Reports.",
        "conclusion": "Pursuant to Section 621(a)(1) of the FCRA, 15 U.S.C. § 1681s(a)(1), the acts and practices violative of Sections 607(a), 607(b), and 607(d) constitute unfair or deceptive acts or practices in violation of Section 5(a) of the FTC Act. Defendants' violations are willful and knowing."
      }
    ]
  },
  "order": {
    "definitions": {
      "Clear(ly) and Conspicuous(ly)": "means that a required disclosure is difficult to miss (i.e., easily noticeable) and easily understandable by ordinary consumers, including in all of the following ways: 1. In any communication that is solely visual or solely audible, the disclosure must be made through the same means through which the communication is presented. In any communication made through both visual and audible means, such as a television advertisement, the disclosure must be presented simultaneously in both the visual and audible portions of the communication even if the representation requiring the disclosure is made in only one means. 2. A visual disclosure, by its size, contrast, location, the length of time it appears, and other characteristics, must stand out from any accompanying text or other visual elements so that it is easily noticed, read, and understood. 3. An audible disclosure, including by telephone or streaming video, must be delivered in a volume, speed, and cadence sufficient for ordinary consumers to easily hear and understand it. 4. In any communication using an interactive electronic medium, such as the Internet or software, the disclosure must be unavoidable. 5. The disclosure must use diction and syntax understandable to ordinary consumers and must appear in each language in which the representation that requires the disclosure appears. 6. The disclosure must comply with these requirements in each medium through which it is received, including all electronic devices and face-to-face communications. 7. The disclosure must not be contradicted or mitigated by, or inconsistent with, anything else in the communication.",
      "Covered Information": "means individually identifiable information from or about an individual consumer, including: (1) first and last name; (2) a physical address; (3) an email address or other online contact information, such as an instant messaging user identifier or a screen name; (4) a telephone number; (5) a persistent identifier, such as a customer number held in a \"cookie,\" a static Internet Protocol (\"IP\") address, a mobile device ID, or processor serial number; (6) date of birth; (7) real property information; (8) corporate affiliations and professional licenses; (9) photos and videos; (10) work history; (11) sex offender status; (12) arrest records; (13) bankruptcy records; (14) liens; (15) eviction records; (16) civil and criminal court record information; (17) traffic tickets or citations; and (18) any information combined with any of (1) through (17) above.",
      "Consumer Report": "means any written, oral, or other communication of any information by a Consumer Reporting Agency bearing on a consumer's credit worthiness, credit standing, credit capacity, character, general reputation, personal characteristics, or mode of living which is used or expected to be used or collected in whole or in part for a Permissible Purpose.",
      "Consumer Reporting Agency": "means any Person which, for monetary fees, dues, or on a cooperative nonprofit basis, regularly engages in whole or in part in the practice of assembling or evaluating consumer credit information or other information on consumers for the purpose of furnishing Consumer Reports to third parties, and which uses any means or facility of interstate commerce for the purpose of preparing or furnishing Consumer Reports.",
      "Covered Business": "means: (1) Corporate Defendant; (2) any business that Corporate Defendant, individually or collectively with Individual Defendant, is a majority owner or controls, directly or indirectly; and (3) any business that Individual Defendant, individually or collectively with Corporate Defendant, is a majority owner or controls directly or indirectly.",
      "Covered Record": "means any written or oral communication that includes any of the following information from or about an individual consumer: (1) sex offender status; (2) arrest records; (3) bankruptcy records; (4) liens; (5) eviction records; (6) civil and criminal court record information; and (7) traffic tickets or citations.",
      "Defendants": "means the Individual Defendant and the Corporate Defendant, individually, collectively, or in any combination.",
      "Corporate Defendant": "means MyLife.com, Inc., and its successors and assigns.",
      "Individual Defendant": "means Jeffrey Tinsley.",
      "Negative Option Feature": "means, in an offer or agreement to sell or provide any product or service, a provision under which the consumer's silence or failure to take affirmative action to reject a product or service or to cancel the agreement is interpreted by the seller or provider as acceptance or continuing acceptance of the offer.",
      "Person": "means any individual, partnership, corporation, trust, estate, cooperative, association, government or governmental subdivision or agency, or other entity.",
      "Permissible Purpose": "1. In response to the order of a court having jurisdiction to issue such an order, or a subpoena issued in connection with proceedings before a Federal grand jury; or\n2. In accordance with the written instructions of the consumer to whom it relates; or\n3. To a person which the Consumer Reporting Agency has reason to believe:\na. intends to use the information in connection with a credit transaction involving the consumer on whom the information is to be furnished and involving the extension of credit to, or review or collection of an account of, the consumer; or\nb. intends to use the information for employment purposes; or\nc. intends to use the information in connection with the underwriting of insurance involving the consumer; or\nd. intends to use the information in connection with a determination of the consumer's eligibility for a license or other benefit granted by a governmental instrumentality required by law to consider an applicant's financial responsibility or status; or\ne. intends to use the information, as a potential investor or servicer, or current insurer, in connection with a valuation of, or an assessment of the credit or prepayment risks associated with, an existing credit obligation; or\nf. otherwise has a legitimate business need for the information:\ni. in connection with a business transaction that is initiated by the consumer; or\nii. to review an account to determine whether the consumer continues to meet the terms of the account; or\ng. executive departments and agencies in connection with the issuance of government-sponsored individually-billed travel charge cards; or\n4. In response to a request by the head of a State or local child support enforcement agency (or a State or local government official authorized by the head of such an agency), if the person making the request certifies to the Consumer Reporting Agency that:\na. the Consumer Report is needed for the purpose of establishing an individual's capacity to make child support payments, determining the appropriate level of such payments, or enforcing a child support order, award, agreement, or judgment;\nb. the parentage of the consumer for the child to which the obligation relates has been established or acknowledged by the consumer in accordance with State laws under which the obligation arises (if required by those laws); and\nc. the Consumer Report will be kept confidential, will be used solely for a purpose described in Definition J.4.a, and will not be used in connection with any other civil, administrative, or criminal proceeding, or for any other purpose; or\n5. To an agency administering a State plan under Section 454 of the Social Security Act (42 U.S.C. § 654) for use to set an initial or modified child support award; or\n6. To the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation or the National Credit Union Administration as part of its preparation for its appointment or as part of its exercise of powers, as conservator, receiver, or liquidating agent for an insured depository institution or insured credit union under the Federal Deposit Insurance Act or the Federal Credit Union Act, or other applicable Federal or State law, or in connection with the resolution or liquidation of a failed or failing insured depository institution or insured credit union, as applicable."
    },
    "provisions": [
      {
        "provision_number": "I",
        "title": "Prohibited Business Activities (Fair Credit Reporting Act)",
        "category": "prohibition",
        "summary": "Defendants are permanently restrained from failing to maintain FCRA-required procedures and from furnishing consumer reports to persons without a permissible purpose.",
        "requirements": [
          {
            "description": "Must not fail to maintain reasonable procedures to limit furnishing of Consumer Reports to Persons with Permissible Purposes, including requiring prospective users to identify themselves, certify purposes, and verify identity",
            "quoted_text": "A. Failing to maintain reasonable procedures designed to limit the furnishing of Consumer Reports to Persons with Permissible Purposes to receive them. Such reasonable procedures shall require that: (1) prospective users of the information identify themselves, certify the purposes for which the information is sought, and certify that the information will be used for no other purpose; and that (2) Defendants make a reasonable effort to verify the identity of a new prospective user and the uses certified by such prospective user prior to furnishing such user a Consumer Report;",
            "deadline": null,
            "verified": true,
            "confidence": 1,
            "quote_start_line": 258,
            "quote_end_line": 265
          },
          {
            "description": "Must not fail to maintain reasonable procedures to assure maximum possible accuracy of information in consumer reports",
            "quoted_text": "B. Failing to maintain reasonable procedures to assure the maximum possible accuracy of the information concerning the individual about whom the report relates;",
            "deadline": null,
            "verified": true,
            "confidence": 1,
            "quote_start_line": 266,
            "quote_end_line": 269
          },
          {
            "description": "Must not fail to provide a notice to users (Attachment A) of their responsibilities under the FCRA",
            "quoted_text": "C. Failing to provide a notice to users (Attached hereto as Attachment A to this Order) of such Person’s responsibilities under the FCRA; and",
            "deadline": null,
            "verified": true,
            "confidence": 1,
            "quote_start_line": 271,
            "quote_end_line": 273
          },
          {
            "description": "Must not furnish a Consumer Report to any Person whom Defendants do not have reason to believe has a Permissible Purpose",
            "quoted_text": "D. Furnishing a Consumer Report to any Person whom Defendants do not have reason to believe has a Permissible Purpose to receive the Consumer Report.",
            "deadline": null,
            "verified": true,
            "confidence": 1,
            "quote_start_line": 275,
            "quote_end_line": 277
          }
        ],
        "statutory_topics": [
          "FCRA"
        ],
        "practice_areas": [
          "Financial Practices"
        ],
        "remedy_types": [
          "Prohibition"
        ]
      },
      {
        "provision_number": "II",
        "title": "Fair Credit Reporting Act Monitoring Program",
        "category": "affirmative_obligation",
        "summary": "Each Covered Business must establish, implement, and maintain a comprehensive monitoring program to regularly assess FCRA applicability and compliance before advertising or offering Covered Information for sale.",
        "requirements": [
          {
            "description": "Document in writing the content, implementation, and maintenance of the Monitoring Program",
            "quoted_text": "A. Document in writing the content, implementation, and maintenance of the Monitoring Program;",
            "deadline": null,
            "verified": true,
            "confidence": 1,
            "quote_start_line": 294,
            "quote_end_line": 295
          },
          {
            "description": "Designate a qualified employee or employees to coordinate and be responsible for the Monitoring Program",
            "quoted_text": "B. Designate a qualified employee or employees to coordinate and be responsible for the Monitoring Program;",
            "deadline": null,
            "verified": true,
            "confidence": 1,
            "quote_start_line": 296,
            "quote_end_line": 297
          },
          {
            "description": "Assess and document at least every 12 months whether Covered Information is a Consumer Report and whether the business is acting as a Consumer Reporting Agency, including review of products, marketing materials, FCRA-prevention measures, and user-use information",
            "quoted_text": "C. Assess and document, prior to the inception of the Monitoring Program and at least once every twelve (12) months thereafter, whether the Covered Information promoted or offered for sale by the Covered Business is a Consumer Report, and whether the Covered Business is acting as a Consumer Reporting Agency. Such assessment shall include, at a minimum, a review of: 1. All products and services offered or sold; 2. Marketing and advertising materials used to offer or sell those products and services (including but not limited to any advertisements, blog posts, testimonials, published statements, customer service scripts, and any method or device used to direct Persons to a website); 3. Any measures to prevent users from using a Covered Business’ products or services for purposes governed by the FCRA (e.g., disclaimers, certifications, account terminations, blocking); and 4. Any information about how users of those products or services use, intend to use, or expect to use those products or services (including but not limited to consumer correspondence, consumer complaints, and consumer testimonials);",
            "deadline": "annually (every 12 months)",
            "verified": true,
            "confidence": 0.85,
            "quote_start_line": 298,
            "quote_end_line": 328
          },
          {
            "description": "Design, implement, maintain, and document FCRA compliance safeguards including: annual staff training, prohibition on marketing Covered Information for Permissible Purposes without FCRA compliance, prepublication review of marketing materials, Clear and Conspicuous disclosure of permissible/impermissible uses, user onboarding procedures with terms, user access controls, and ongoing reviews/audits of user practices",
            "quoted_text": "D. Design, implement, maintain, and document safeguards to assure FCRA compliance. Such safeguards must include, at a minimum: 1. Training of all officers, employees, agents, and independent contractors, at onboarding and at least every twelve (12) months thereafter, on the FCRA’s legal requirements and activities that would violate those requirements; 2. Refraining from advertising, marketing, promoting, describing, or offering for sale any product or service that involves Covered Information as suitable or appropriate for any Permissible Purpose, unless the requirements of the FCRA and this Order that would apply to a Consumer Report are satisfied as to that product or service; 3. Prepublication review of all marketing and advertising materials used to offer or sell those products and services (including but not limited to any advertisements, blog posts, testimonials, published statements, customer service scripts, and any method or device used to direct Persons to a website); 4. Clearly and Conspicuously disclosing permissible and impermissible uses of any Covered Information under the FCRA and this Order prior to providing or disclosing such information; 5. Procedures to onboard users, including requiring users to agree to contracts or terms and conditions governing FCRA compliance and Clear and Conspicuous disclosure of such terms and conditions; 6. User access controls, such as controls on the number of Covered Records obtained per day; and 7. Ongoing reviews, tests, or audits of the ways that users use or expect to use that Covered Business’ products or services;",
            "deadline": null,
            "verified": true,
            "confidence": 1,
            "quote_start_line": 329,
            "quote_end_line": 355
          },
          {
            "description": "Evaluate and adjust the Monitoring Program in light of any changes to business operations or arrangements, and at minimum evaluate every 12 months and implement modifications based on results",
            "quoted_text": "E. Evaluate and adjust the Monitoring Program in light of any changes to the business’ operations or business arrangements, or any other circumstance that the business knows or has reason to know may materially affect the Monitoring Program’s effectiveness. At a minimum, each Covered Business must evaluate the Monitoring Program every twelve (12) months and implement modifications based on the results; and",
            "deadline": "annually (every 12 months)",
            "verified": true,
            "confidence": 0.85,
            "quote_start_line": 357,
            "quote_end_line": 369
          },
          {
            "description": "At least once every 12 months, provide the written Monitoring Program and its evaluations/updates, and the FCRA assessments, to the Covered Business's board of directors or governing body (or senior compliance officer if no such body exists)",
            "quoted_text": "F. At least once every twelve (12) months, provide (1) the written program required by Subsection II.A and any evaluations thereof or updates thereto, and (2) the assessments and documentation required by Subsection II.C to the Covered Business’s board of directors or governing body or, if no such board or equivalent governing body exists, to a senior officer responsible for regulatory compliance.",
            "deadline": "annually (every 12 months)",
            "verified": true,
            "confidence": 1,
            "quote_start_line": 370,
            "quote_end_line": 374
          }
        ],
        "statutory_topics": [
          "FCRA"
        ],
